"We couldn't press the switch to take away everything from China," said Emily Waynestan, a researcher at Georgetown University Security and Emerging Technology Center.

The dependence of the chip industry's dependence on China highlights that the close but contradictory economic relationship between China and the United States has challenged both parties.

This tension also reflects the trip to China ’s visit to China. She tried to testify carefully and criticized some Chinese actions. At the same time, she insisted that the United States did not intend to cut off the relationship with China.

Yellen [Critical](https://cn.nytimes.com/usa/20230707/yellen-china-companies-meetings/)China's recent punishment measures for foreign companies, including restrictions on some mineral exports for chip manufacturing. She said that such measures are the reason why the Bayeng government hopes that American manufacturers will reduce dependence on China. But she still affirmed the strategic and importance of US -China relations.

advertise

"I have clearly stated that the United States does not seek a comprehensive separation of the economy of the two countries," said at the round table conference held by Yellen and the round table held in Huamei. "We seek diversification rather than decoupling. The decoupling between the two largest economies in the world will destroy global economic stability, and it is almost impossible to do it."

Bayeng Government Preparation [Start a lot of investment](https://cn.nytimes.com/technology/20230104/us-chip-making-china-invest/)The US semiconductor manufacturing industry attracts factories to leave China. Later this year, the Ministry of Commerce is expected to start funding to help enterprises establish chip manufacturing facilities in the United States. These funds [with conditions](https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/03/business/economy/chip-industry-congress.html): Enterprises accepting funds cannot expand high -tech manufacturing facilities in China.

The U.S. government is still considering further restrictions on chips that can be exported to China as an enlarged and finally completing the [Comprehensive Restrictions] introduced in October last year(https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/27/business/the-biden-administration-is-weighing-further-controls-on-chinese-technology.html)Part of the measure.

According to people familiar with the matter, these measures may include [restricting sales of China](https://cn.nytimes.com/business/20230629/biden-administration-ai-chips-china/)Advanced chips used for artificial intelligence, new restrictions on Chinese enterprises using American cloud computing services, and restricting [American Risk Capital](https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/09/business/us-china-investing-tech-biden.html)Investment in the Chinese chip industry.

The U.S. government has also been considering stopping issuing licenses to some American chip manufacturers to prevent them from continuing to sell products to China Telecom Corporation Huawei.

Japan and the Netherlands are the location of many advanced chip manufacturing equipment manufacturers, partly due to the pressure of the United States, and they have also applied new restrictions on sales of China.

advertise

China has also introduced its own restrictions, including new export controls for mineral manufacturing for chip manufacturing.

When the United States and Europe have all introduced stricter regulatory measures and new incentive plans, when global chip companies choose the next key investment destination, they are increasingly investing in outside China. However, these facilities may take several years to build, which means that any change in the global semiconductor market will be gradual.

John Neuifu, president of the semiconductor industry association representing the chip industry, said in a statement that the continuously upgraded control measures constitute a major risk of global competitiveness in the United States.

"China is the world's largest semiconductor market. Our companies must carry out business there to achieve sustainable growth and innovation, and maintain their position in the world's competitors," he said. "We call for unintentional and lasting damage to protect national security and not cope with the chip industry, and avoid the solution of future conflict upgrades."

