Description: According to statistics, the overall debt in China has reached 282%of the annual economic output. How is such a deep debt dilemma formed? What will this impact on the global economy? Is there any solution? Here is an analysis. Pool Photo by Mark Schiefelbein Treasury Minister Yellen tried to persuade China to strengthen cooperation during his visit to alleviate the debt crisis of low -income countries. The picture shows Yellen meet with Chinese Prime Minister Li Qiang in Beijing.

Images: ["[CHINA-DEBT-02...](https://static01.nyt.com/images/2023/07/07/multimedia/CHINA-DEBT-02-pckt/CHINA-DEBT-02-pckt-master1050.jpg)"]

Category: 中国

Type: Article

<!--METADATA-->

![](Images/cnnytimes/2023-07-10T05-41-13-08-00/CHINA-DEBT-02-pckt-master1050.jpg)China has provided [nearly $ 1 trillion loan] to about 150 developing countries(https://cn.nytimes.com/business/20230328/china-loans-bailouts-debt/)However, it has been reluctant to avoid huge debt owed by countries that are difficult to balance. This is to a certain extent because China also faces debt bombs: local governments, its subordinate outford financing institutions, and real estate developers owe trillions of dollars.

[Minister of Finance Yellen](https://cn.nytimes.com/usa/20230707/yellen-china-companies-meetings/)One of the main issues during the visit to China is whether she can persuade China to strengthen cooperation to solve the continuous evolutionary debt crisis faced by low -income countries. However, China's state -owned banking system is facing a much larger loan loss in the territory and is cautious about receiving foreign loan losses.

** How much debt does China have? **

Because the official data is very small, it is difficult to know the exact number. Researchers at Morgan Chase calculated last month to calculate the overall debt (including family, enterprises, and governments) in China last month. In contrast, the average proportion of developed economies in the world is 256%, and the United States is 257%.

advertise

The difference between China and most countries is that debt is so fast compared to its economic scale. In contrast, the growth rate of Japanese debt in the United States and even the debt is slower. The sharp increase in Chinese debt has made management debt more difficult. Since the global financial crisis 15 years ago, China's debt has doubled compared with its economic scale.

Compared with its domestic debt, the loan provided by China to developing countries is small, accounting for less than 6%of China's annual economic output. But these loans are particularly sensitive in politics. Despite strict review, Chinese social media still complained from time to time, saying that banks should lend money to domestic poor families and regions, not abroad. Therefore, the huge loss of these loans will be very unpopular in China.

![](Images/cnnytimes/2023-07-10T05-41-13-08-00/CHINA-DEBT-01-kqjp-master1050.jpg)Chinese construction workers at a construction site in Sri Lanka go home from get off work. Adam dean for the new york times

** How did China fall into such a deep debt dilemma? **

The first is real estate. The industry is facing the problem of excessive construction, price decline, and potential buyers. In the past two years, dozens of real estate developers who have borrowed money from overseas investors have had debt defaults. In recent days, there have been two more. For a long time, developers have been very difficult to repay the huge debt from Chinese banks.

Local governments' debts make the problem more complicated. In the past ten years, many provinces and cities have established special financial institutions. They have less supervised supervision and a large scale of debt. Officials use these money to pay daily expenses, including interests of other loans, as well as the construction of roads, bridges, parks and other infrastructure.

The issue of real estate and government debt overlap. Over the years, the main source of revenue from the local area is to sell long -term lease contracts for developers to sell state -owned land. As many private developers have exhausted funds for bidding land, land sales revenue has decreased. Instead, local financing institutions raised a lot of debt and purchased land that these developers were unable to undertake at high prices. As the real estate market continues to weaken, many of these financing institutions have fallen into trouble.

advertise

The debt is more and more accumulated. Credit rating agency Fitch rating estimates that the debt of local governments is equivalent to about 30%of China's annual economic output. Fitch said that the debt owed by these auxiliary financing units is equivalent to 40%to 50%of the nation's output, but because local governments borrow money and transfer their debts to financing units, dual calculations may occur.

** Why is this important? **

For any government or enterprise, if funds are effectively used, borrowing will have good economic significance. A large amount of borrowing but not enough funds to be returned can be in trouble and it is difficult to repay the loan party. This is the case in China. As the economy slows down, more and more local governments and its financing units are unable to continue paying debt interest. Chain reaction means that many places lack funds to pay public services, medical insurance or pensions.

The issue of debt also makes it difficult for Chinese banks to accept the loss of loans to low -income countries. However, many of them, such as Sri Lanka, Pakistan, and [Surinan](https://cn.nytimes.com/world/20230628/suriname-china-imf/)Nowadays, they are facing [considerable economic difficulties](https://cn.nytimes.com/business/20230328/china-loans-bailouts-debt/) 。

![](Images/cnnytimes/2023-07-10T05-41-13-08-00/CHINA-DEBT-03-hkfv-master1050.jpg)Pakistan is one of the largest borrowing countries in China and one of the countries facing a serious debt crisis. Kiana Hayeri for the New York Times

Nearly two -thirds of development in the world depend on the export of commodities. The World Bank predicts that the price of commodities this year will decrease 21%compared with last year.

In 2010, only 5%of China's overseas loan portfolios were used to support borrowing countries in trouble. Virginia Williamsburg and the executive director of Aiddata University, Bradeli Pax, said that this number has reached 60%today.

advertise

China is by far the largest sovereign loan country to lend to developing countries, although Western hedge funds have also purchased many bonds in these countries. These bonds often use fixed interest rates. However, Chinese banks tend to use adjustable interest rates linked to Western interest rates to issue US dollar loans. As the Federal Reserve raised interest rates since March 2022, developing countries are facing the owe of China [debt has soared](https://cn.nytimes.com/business/20221008/china-debt-economy-global-slowdown/)question.

If measures are not taken to reduce debt, many of the most poorest governments in the world will continue to spend huge sums of money to repay debts. These money can have been used in schools, hospitals and other services. "The biggest losers will eventually be ordinary people in developing countries. Because the government is carrying unsustainable debt, they will be deprived of basic public services," Pax said.

** What is the solution? **The host of Beijing and the capital of China guards the current economic priority. Yellen will try to learn more about China's economic plan, but it cannot affect these plans.

Last winter, 21 Bank of China agreed to allow a local government financing institution in Southwest China to extend the upcoming loan for 20 years, and stated that it only needs to repay interest in the first 10 years without repayment. However, this arrangement means that the bank has suffered heavy losses, and local financial institutions in almost every province have fallen into a similar dilemma.

advertise

However, it is difficult to solve the debt problem of developing countries. "Yellen persuaded China to have limited ability to accept debt records," said former U.S. Ministry of Finance Mark Sobel. He also said, "The United States and Yellen have little influence."

