![](Images/cnnytimes/2023-07-10T08-15-16-08-00/06Yan1-jumbo.jpg)Last Monday, Yan Mingfu died in Beijing at the age of 91. He was the son of the underground party of the Communist Party of China. He later served as Mao Zedong's translation. As a negotiating representative, he tried to resolve the deadlock between the Chinese Communist Party and the student protesters who occupied Tiananmen in 1989.

![](Images/cnnytimes/2023-07-10T08-15-16-08-00/06Yan1-jumbo.jpg)Yan Mingfu in 1995. "At the critical moment in 1989, his human nature defeated the party spirit," a student leader described the role of Yan Mingfu's protest in Tiananmen Square. Eric li/Southchina morning post, via getty images

His daughter Yan Lan published in China's "Caixin" magazine [article](https://mini.caixin.com/2023-07-05/102072666.html), Confirmed his death. She did not explain the specific cause of death, but Yan Mingfu suffered from multiple diseases in his later years.

"Dad walked calmly and drew an end to his ups and downs," Yan Lan wrote.

In the critical period of the Cold War in China, Yan Mingfu was pushed into the vortex of political situation. During the period when Mao Zedong filed with the Soviet Union in the 1950s, and later, Yan Mingfu was Mao Zedong's Russian translation. In 1989, when the Soviet leader Gorbachev visited Beijing to meet the cracks, he became accompanied by Chinese leaders.

advertise

However, Yan Mingfu's most intense and most painful political event may be the democratic protest in Tiananmen Square in 1989, which was shadowed to Gorbachev's visit. Yan Mingfu became a negotiating representative, talking to Chinese intellectuals with protesters and Chinese intellectuals who tried to stop bloody suppression.

"Mr. Yan Mingfu followed the people of the Communist Party in his life, but at the critical moment in 1989, his human nature defeated the party spirit."(https://www.rfa.org/mandarin/Xinwen/6-07032023115209.html)Written. "Such people are rare within the CCP."

On November 11, 1931, Yan Mingju was born in Beijing and ranked older among the six children. His father, Yan Baohang, is an official of the Governor's Kuomintang government. In 1937, [secretly joined the hostile Communist Party](http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:iqLNNtnSCT8J:dangshi.people.com.cn/n/2015/0902/c85037-27542049.html&hl=en&gl=tw&strip=1&vwsrc=0), Become an underground party. His mother, Gao Suntong, is a housewife.

Yan Mingfu wrote in a memoir published in 2015 that with the advancement of Japan's invasion of China, their family kept relocating, and finally settled in Chongqing, southwestern cities in China, and became the Kuomintang's base camp during the war.

When he was young, Yan Mingfu had witnessed the mysterious visitors -the contact person of the Communist Party, secretly slipped into the room on the second floor of his house to see his father.

"On the surface, he was playing mahjong," Yan Mingfu wrote in his memoir. "It's actually a meeting."

advertise

Later, their family moved to the northeast near the Soviet border, and Yan Mingfu decided to learn Russian. After the Communist Party led by Mao Zedong in 1949, Yan Mingfu served as a translation for government officials. At that time, China studied the Soviet Union, and Yan Ming resumed the translation of Soviet consultants in the Mao Zedong government.

In 1955, he married Wu Keliang, who was also translated. She died in 2015. According to [Family Memoirs published by Daughter Yan Lan](https://www.harpercollins.com/products/the-house-of-yan-lan-yan?variant=32207726018594), The two elderly people also have a grandson.

Yan Mingfu accompanied Chinese leaders to visit the Soviet Union, and served as Mao Zedong's interpreter in Moscow's treacherous negotiations in 1957. At that time, the relationship between the two countries had begun to complicate due to ideological and foreign policy tensions.

On the hot day in August 1958, Mao Zedong exchanged opinions with the visited Soviet leader Khrushchev while swimming. Yan Mingfu and another translator also followed the pool, and worked hard to hear what the two leaders said, and then translated it loudly to each other.

"When they swim and go ashore, we are already sweating," Yan Mingfu recalled.

In the following 20 years, with the turbulence of Mao Zedong's revolutionary situation, and officials close to the Soviet Union have become increasingly suspicious, Yan Mingfu was deeply implicated. In 1967, he was accused of being prison for Su Xiu agents and counter -revolutionary.

His wife Wu Keliang was also severely reviewed and put into the countryside. In 1975, with the gradual sound of the "Cultural Revolution", Yan Mingfu was released, and the husband and wife were able to reunite with their daughters.

![](Images/cnnytimes/2023-07-10T08-15-16-08-00/06YAN2-jumbo.jpg)In April 1989, a student protest on the Tiananmen Square in Beijing. For several months, the government is discussing how to deal with the increasingly large protesters. Peter Turnley/GetTyimages

In 1989, Yan Mingfu served as Minister of the Communist Party of China, and the ministry was responsible for dealing with the relationship with intellectuals and ethnic minorities and religious groups.

When the students occupied Tiananmen Square, shouted democratic reform and the demands of the end of corruption, the reform sent by Zhao Ziyang, the general secretary of the party, sent Yan Mingfu as a mediation person. Zhao Ziyang tried to persuade the students to end the hunger strike and ensure that Gorbachev's visit to Beijing was smooth.

advertise

Deng Xiaoping, the top leader of China, asked Yan Mingfu to attend talks with Gorbachev. "For so many years, Mingfu has been participating in these negotiations of China and the Soviet Union," Yan Mingfu described Deng Xiaoping's instructions in this memoir, "this time it also allowed Mingfu to participate."

In the meeting with the student leader, Yan Mingfu tried to persuade them to stop hunger strike, because the hunger strike had pushed the political enthusiasm of the protesters to the extreme. He and other officials also sought help from liberal journalists, scholars and intellectuals, and tried their best to fight for protesters' understanding.

But the CCP's hardliners were anxious to show off their cards and refused to make any major concessions. The enthusiastic democratic protest movement will not be easily soothed by negotiations.

In mid -May, [Yan Mingfu adventure to Tiananmen Square](https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCBKDRq35-L8xev4O7ZqBeLg/community?lb=UgkxuJxCEG1fa-OjnvwvCOYeE9HzC1JWLKD5)For the support of the protesters, many people are unable to get up because of refusing to eat. He assured the protesters that the government would consider their demands and guarantee that they would not settle their accounts after autumn.In the end, he begged: "If the students do not believe my guarantee, you can bring me Yan Mingfu back to school for hostages!"

advertise

Zhou Ru wrote that Yan Mingfu's words and deeds made him understand that "the Communists are not a piece of iron."

Deng Xiaoping settled the efforts of getting rid of the deadlock in a peaceful way. Less than three weeks later, the army entered the center of Beijing and fired to the protests and onlookers. Hundreds of them -according to some estimates that are thousands of civilians.

Yan Mingfu was surrendered. In his subsequent political career, he served as the deputy minister of the Ministry of Civil Affairs, and later chairman of the Chinese Charity Federation of Charity in the government background.

After retiring, he wrote many memoirs. His article did not mention the history of the 1980s, and reflected the official discussion on that era was still very sensitive.

