Rainstorms in southwestern Japan have caused landslides. Two people have died and six disappeared.

According to ABC and Agence France -Presse, the local fire department reported on Monday (July 10) that a landslide occurred at night in Fukuoka, causing a 77 -year -old woman in the local countryside to die. , I was taken to the hospital. A man in Yamaguchi was killed in a car that fell into a flood.

Landscapes also occurred in Karatsu, which are adjacent to Fukuoka, and six people disappeared in the local area.

The Japan Meteorological Administration has issued a warning of the heavy rainfall to various cities in Fukuoka, emphasizing that this will be the strongest rainfall experienced by the area in the region. The Meteorological Bureau said that some kind of disaster may have occurred at present, and the situation is very urgent, and it is necessary to ensure the safety of the people.

The authorities issued non -compulsory evacuation orders to some areas of Fukuoka, Daben and neighboring counties. These counties are also opening asylum places and resettled the evacuation of the masses. The Japanese Prime Minister's Office claims that a working group has been established to coordinate the response to rainfall measures.

Shinkansen bullet train services between western Hiroshima and Fukuoka also suspended due to heavy rainfall.

Japan is currently in the annual rainy season, and it often brings heavy rain, sometimes causing floods and landslides, causing casualties. Scientists point out that climate change is intensifying the risk of heavy rain in Japan and other places.

In 2021, ATAMI, Shizuoka Prefecture, Japan (ATAMI), caused a landslide due to rainfall, and 27 people were killed. In 2018, the Japanese rainy season caused floods and landslides in the west, causing more than 200 people to die.

