The German Chemical Group is investing in modern factories and green technology -but mainly outside Europe, the largest union in the industry warns.

German Chemical and Energy Industry Trade Union IG BCE Chairman Michael Vasilianis(Michael Vassiliadis)Said: "Investment in new factories and new technologies ... is out of Germany." He added that "since the emergence of energy issues", this trend has accelerated.

Vasilianis said that the main beneficiaries are China and the United States. These two countries provide enterprises with "full sets". In addition to tax benefits, they also include providing green energy and regulatory rapid approval.

European countries compete for foreign direct investment(FDI)Competition is increasingly fierce. German Institute of Economics(German Economic Institute)It is said that because companies will invest in overseas, Germany encountered a record deficit last year, and said that this situation was "worrying."

Last year, the U.S. government announced the "Reduction of Inflation"(IRA)The huge subsidies for various green technology investment are designed to attract foreign direct investment for key areas. Vasilianis said that China also uses the treasury to support certain industries, one of which is the chemical industry.

The Chinese government, which is difficult to cope with the long -term slowdown of the economy, especially welcomes foreign direct investment to enter high -tech fields such as advanced manufacturing, information technology and scientific research, because China is striving to make the industry climb upstream to the value chain.

Wasilianis is both the person in charge of the union and BASF(BASF)Member of the Supervisory Board. He said the German chemical group is a typical example of investing in the most advanced technology in China.

The world's largest chemical company is currently building a petrochemical base that invests 10 billion euros in Zhanjiang. Based on the headquarters of this German group located in the port of Ludwig Port, the base will use "cutting -edge technology" and "maximum ... sustainable standards". At the same time, the company warned it that it would "permanently" reduce its business in Europe.

Vasilianis said that the support of Chinese authorities has made this investment possible. China will build a wind power field near the base to meet the company's requirements for a large amount of cheap green energy.

Kepler Cheuvreux's chemical industry research joint director Christian Fayz(ChristianFaitz)He said he believes that Europe will not build any new ammonia factories. As a raw material required for hydrogen -powered vehicles, ammonia plays an important role in the net zero emissions economy. At the same time, BASF closed one of the two ammonia factories located in Ludwig Port on the grounds of high energy costs.

"I hope (Europe) politicians can realize these trends." He added that this trend may threaten the industrial growth of continental Europe.

VCI of the German Chemical Industry Association said that companies in the industry cannot invest in China, which accounts for about 43%of the global chemical industry market.

VCI added that the German Chemical Group has "expanded" investment in China in recent years, and one -fifth of the foreign investment in the industry has finally flowed into China.

