The tide of immigration after Hong Kong's "recovering the Central Movement" continues, which is also reflected in the number of people who have lost from Hong Kong for primary and secondary school students. According to the latest statistical report issued by the Hong Kong media "Ming Pao", Hong Kong lost a total of 27,000 primary and secondary school students last year.

The report pointed out that as of September 2022, more than 27,000 primary and secondary school students no longer stayed in Hong Kong for further studies, which was a peak in recent years. Compared with September 2018 to September 2019, the number of local primary and secondary school students' net reduction was only 2,429; and from September 2019 to September 2022, the three years after the "counterfeiting" and the new crown epidemic, Hong Kong has reducing the cumulative reduction in Hong Kong. Nearly 68,000 primary and secondary school students.

Some local middle school principal said that the wave of dropping out of school has not yet been topped. It is expected that the number of middle schools will be further reduced in the new school year, and the rate of losses can be slightly declined in one or two years.

The Hong Kong Education Bureau said that parents have the right to choose to go to school for their children, and the movement such as transferring schools, moving to the Mainland, and overseas education are all normal.

After Hong Kong's "counter -delivery" movement, the wave of immigration appeared. According to the first "Administrative Report" published in the Hong Kong Chief Executive Li Jiachang in October 2022, the official estimation was that about 140,000 workers lost in Hong Kong in the past two years before the official estimation.

