At present, the Chinese economy is depressed, leading to debt problems. According to the New York Times, due to the few official data, it is difficult to know the exact number of Chinese debt. However, according to the calculation of Morgan Chase researchers, the overall debt in China has reached 282%of its annual economic output (GDP), which is significantly higher than the average proportion of global developed economies of 256%and 257%of the United States.

It is reported that China's debt is so fast compared to its economic scale, making it more difficult for management debt. Since the global financial crisis 15 years ago, China's debt has doubled compared with its economic scale. The cause of the increase in China's debt is mainly due to the large -scale debt of the real estate industry and local governments that have fallen prices after excessive construction.

It is reported that according to Fitch rating estimates, the debt under the name of the local government of China has reached about 30%of the national GDP, while the debt under the name of the subsidiary financing unit has reached 40%to 50%. However, because some local governments will transfer debt to financing units after borrowing money, repeated calculations may occur.

The report also said that China has provided nearly 1 trillion US dollars of loans to about 150 developing countries, but has been reluctant to be exempted from huge debts owed to countries that are difficult to balance. This is to a certain extent because China also faces "debt bombs", that is, local governments, its subordinates off -balance sheet financing institutions, and real estate developers owe trillions of dollars.

The report pointed out that the scale of loans provided by China to developing countries is smaller than its domestic debt, accounting for less than 6%of the annual economic output. But these loans are particularly sensitive in politics. The huge loss of these loans will be very unpopular in China. Its debt problem also makes it difficult for Chinese banks to accept the loss of loans to low -income countries.

The report also pointed out that with the decline of the economy, more and more local governments and its financing units in China are unable to continue paying debt interest, and the chain reaction generates is unable to pay public services, medical insurance and pensions.

As for the solution, it is reported that it is difficult for China's domestic debt to solve quickly, and it can only get rid of government construction projects and huge national security expenditures with debt -driven government, and turn to economy based on consumer expenditures and services.

